Census Progress

LD

8/6/2020

Purpose

The goal is to look at how regions have progressed since the response rate plateau mid-May. While more affluent regions (such as Santa Clarita) started out with high response rates and continue to have high self-response rates, the harder-to-count regions (such as SELA, South LA, etc.) have consistently made the response rate gains week-to-week.

In this way we hope to show that the hard work of our partners has been the reason we have got so far with the count during a pandemic.

Method

  • I will pull in response rates from mid-May to the present. I don’t think I need a time series, just an overall net change since the plateau. I will pull in regional response rates as well as census tracts–we’ll see which looks better.

  • I may want to aggregate to COVID neighborhood boundaries, we’ll see.

2 Summarize by Neighborhood

  • Use the COVID-Census crosswalk to map response rate gains by COVID polygon.

  • Multiply the percent intersect by:

    • the number of households that responded
    • the total number of households

  • Group by neighborhood name

  • Sum proportional number of responding households, total number of households

    • divide to get the response rate by neighborhood
# get tract response rates 
covidpoly_sum <- lapply(resp_list_ct, function(x) x %>% 
                       
                       # filter only LA tracts
                       filter(GEOID10 %like% "06037") %>% 
                       select(GEOID10, resp_house10, housecur, access_date) %>% 
                       
                       # join covid poly crosswalk
                       full_join(xwalk, by=c("GEOID10"="GEOID")) %>% 
                       
                       # proportional allocation to covid neighborhood
                       mutate(resp_hh_conv = resp_house10 * prc_int, 
                              tot_hh_conv = housecur * prc_int) %>% 
                       
                       group_by(lac_place_name, access_date) %>% 
                         
                       #  calculate neighborhood response rate by dividng responding hh by total hh   
                       summarize(resp_conv = sum(resp_hh_conv, na.rm = T),
                                 tothh_conv = sum(tot_hh_conv, na.rm = T),
                                 resp_prc = resp_conv/tothh_conv))

Summary Stats

COVID/HTC Typology

  • The COVID/HTC Typology is determined by medians:

    • Communities with COVID-19 case rates higher than the median are considered “higher COVID” communities.

    • Communities with a mean HTC score (mean of HTC score of all census tracts in the community) higher than the median mean HTC score are considered “harder to count” communities.

# load typology data to get mean HTC score from covid analysis
typology <- read.csv(paste0(covidroot, "covid_dem_resp.csv"), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)


# make covid/htc typology
covidpoly_gain <- 
covidpoly_gain %>% 
  left_join(typology %>% 
              select(lac_place_name, mean_htc), by="lac_place_name") %>% 
  
  mutate(htc_typ = ifelse(mean_htc > summary(typology$mean_htc)[3], "High HTC", "Low HTC"),
         covid_typ = ifelse(cases_per100k > summary(covidpoly_gain$cases_per100k)[3], "High COVID", "Low COVID"),
         typ = paste0(htc_typ, ", ", covid_typ))


table(covidpoly_gain$htc_typ, covidpoly_gain$covid_typ)
##           
##            High COVID Low COVID
##   High HTC        110        41
##   Low HTC          41       110
  • 110 of 151 harder-to-count communities have high rates of COVID-19.
